# Replies observed from a de-primed ("cold") Axon dongle, per
# docs/FINDINGS.md and the research/python-tests axon_libusb_test
# status-output CSVs.
#
# Format: two 64-byte HID input reports, one per logical reply,
# separated by a blank section header comment. Both are padded to
# the full 64-byte HID report size.
#
# --- cold identify reply ---
# rx[0]=0x04 report id, rx[1]=0x01, rx[2]=0xFA ("no servo" status
# low byte). The remaining bytes are whatever stale data was in the
# dongle's buffer — we zero them for determinism since the protocol
# layer only inspects rx[1], rx[2], rx[5], rx[7].
04 01 fa 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00
00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00
00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00
00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00

# --- cold read NACK reply ---
# rx[0]=0x04 report id, rx[1]=0xCD (the command byte echoed back
# instead of 0x01), rx[2]=0x02 (the "command not executed" status
# low byte we observed in axon_libusb_test2/test_status output).
# rx[3]=0x00 addr echo, rx[4]=0x3B length echo. Data bytes are
# stale/garbage from the dongle's last primed read — zeroed here
# for determinism; the protocol layer must reject this reply on
# the rx[1]/rx[2] gate before it ever reads the data payload.
04 cd 02 00 3b 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00
00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00
00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00
00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00
